  footnotes: []
english:
  title: At the Hojae Gathering on the Lantern Festival, I Received the Character 'Leak'
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I wore hemp robes, others donned fine furs.
    When others dwelt in glorious halls, I lived in a humble hut.
    Heaven's gifts were never meant to be equal—
    I harbor no grudge against others, yet they mock me still.

    What night is this? The night of the first full moon!
    At the noble house's splendid feast, I follow the guests behind.
    Why speak of the ten thousand affairs of mankind?
    My body is strong—let me contend before the wine cup!

    Friend, pour again and turn the lamp once more.
    Let us drink with abandon until the dawn bells sound.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Lantern Festival' (元宵/정월 보름) refers to the celebration of the first full moon of the lunar year, traditionally a time of festivities and gathering.
  - key: ''
    value: The character 'leak' (漏) likely refers to the water clock (漏刻) used to mark time, suggesting the poem was written during an evening gathering where such timekeeping devices were present.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem contrasts the speaker's humble circumstances with others' wealth, yet celebrates finding joy and fellowship despite such disparities.
